<br>
One artist that comes to mind is Michael W. Smith.  Songs like &quot;Picture Perfect&quot; where he sings, &quot;You don't have to be picture perfect to be in my world.&quot;  Songs that if the singer was not labeled a Christian music artist, that you would not think the songs had anything to do with Christianity.<br>
<br>
Personally, I have a bit of a problem with it.  It's one reason I've tired of so much CCM today.  With songs like MWS's &quot;Picture Perfect,&quot; I'll never be in his world so that song seems really shallow to me.  And maybe it's just me, but I think the song would have been better if he had sung, &quot;You don't have to be picture perfect to be in God's world.&quot;  Something that minor to take the focus off the singer where it doesn't belong and onto God where it does belong.<br>
<br>
I think I've become un-hip.  Whereas I use to think CCM was all cool as it was contemporary and had all the modern beats and all that, I find myself tuning out of those kinds of stations more.  I don't care if I pick a station that just sings old hymns.  There's something in me that cries out for more of Jesus and less of this world the longer I live in it.<br>
<br>
I love &quot;the Jesus record&quot; which was the project Rich Mullins was working on when he died.  Inside the cover of the album it says this...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>On September 10, 1997, Rich Mullins sat down in an old, abandoned church and played nin songs that were to be part of a record he had affectionately termed &quot;Ten Songs About Jesus.&quot;  This was a new project Rich was just starting called &quot;The Jesus Record,&quot; a project Rich said was &quot;needed&quot; - for himself and his friends.  Just nine short days later, Rich left this world and went to meet Jesus, His savior and Lord.  Recorded only on a cassette with a cheap, battery-operated recorder, the nine songs were, to say the least, rough.  But the cassette was salvaged and cleaned up so that these nine demos could be put onto a cd.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I read that and I can't help but think God was sending such a powerful message.  Rich's heart seemed burden by the secularism in the CCM industry to the point he wanted to make an album all about Jesus.  Such a simple theme and thought.  And just nine days after sitting down to play those songs, the Lord took him home.  And somehow in the wreckage, that little tape survived as though God was saying - this is what I want.  Though the tape was battered and the quality of sound probably diminished some in the wreckage - perhaps that too is a sign.<br>
<br>
I remember another singer who tragically lost his life, Keith Green forbid them putting a price tag on his albums for awhile because he was tired of the commercialization of the gospel.  Though he finally allowed the price to be put back on because there were lots of people who needed food and shelter and needed the money to pay for it.<br>
<br>
Why does it seem that the Christian music artists who really get it lose their lives tragically?<br>
<br>
