<br>
Here's a question - would you stay at a church if you never once heard the pastor say the name of Jesus or God or Bible?  I've heard plenty of sermons in my life that sound very humanist - how to live a more wholesome better life with no emphasis whatsoever on God or Jesus.  I'm not comfortable with those churches and pastors who preach on how to be better people and never or rarely say the name of God or Jesus.  There is power in the name of Jesus and I can't explain the power I've seen the Lord exhibit when I say the name of Jesus.  It's how we know who truly is a Christian.  It's why I say Jesus more than God - because whenever you recognize Jesus, you recognize God as well, but not everyone who says the name God recognizes Jesus and if they don't recognize Jesus, they are recognizing a false god.  How do I know if you are my brother or sister in Christ?  If you recognize Jesus for who He is.  There are some Christian music artists who I wonder about.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't understand why someone that has made a profession of Christianity is required to make all their music sacred. We, all of us, spend time on other projects. We don't make every topic of discussion, art project, friendship, book we read, etc, etc, etc Christian. So, why should they be put in that box either? Does writing/singing a song that is not sacred lessen their relationship with God? I wouldn't think so.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Let me say I don't mind there being a song on an album that makes no mention of God or Jesus or the Bible or any direct matter of faith.  They do have a place.  What bothers me is when a Christian artist produces an album and there is no direct mention in any of the songs.  When none of them do.  They've got 10 songs (generally) on an album.  As Christian music artists, I would expect at least one song (if not more) to make some direct mention.  It's not a requirement by any means.  It makes me question - where's their heart and what are their goals?  Is their goal to sell as many albums as they can or is their goal to fulfill the great commission?<br>
<br>
